Overview of Focus Management

We’ve seen some examples of focus management in the CampSpots app so far.

When we manage the user’s keyboard focus point with skip links, that’s an example of the most basic form of focus management.

In the MegaNav, we are handling focus management in a couple of different ways. The user isn’t able to Tab with the keyboard into submenus that aren’t open. If they hit the Escape key when the menu is open, their focus goes from a submenu link back to the button they were on when they opened the menu.

Being able to programmatically move focus to different parts of your application is a necessary skill when building interactive web applications.

Focus Management in the Component Sandbox

To look at focus management more deeply, we’ll revisit the Component Sandbox served by the local dev server at http://localhost:1234/component-sandbox.

Examining the Modal Dialog

This time in the sandbox we’ll look at the modal dialog.

Modals are a very popular (and often over used) pattern used for all kinds of things, from getting relatively basic input from the user all the way to more problematic implementations like loading entire tab switchers or slideshow components inside.

Because these patterns are so common it’s important to know how to make them accessible. So for our purposes, we’ll examine what goes into making an accessible modal dialog.

Typically an interaction with a focusable element will fire an event that opens a modal. In the sandbox, clicking the “Launch modal” button will open the modal.

The modal itself is an interstitial or some sort of layer that pops up on the screen, while the background is greyed out with a screen curtain.

In the sandbox example, opening the modal brings focus to the “Confirm Selection” H1. The Tab key takes us to the focusable “Cool” button in the dialog. We are not able to Tab into the focusable items that are back behind the modal. This is the desired behavior.

There is some subjectivity as to whether or not you trap users in the modal. I decided to prevent items in the background from being focusable but allow the browser controls to still be reached. Some implementations will prevent this and instead cycle through the items in the modal with each press of the Tab key, known as an intentional focus trap.

The most important part is that focus is moved into the thing that opened and neither screen reader nor sighted mouse users are able to interact with the items behind the darkened screen curtain.

When the modal is closed (either with the Escape key or hitting the “Cool” button), focus returns to the “Launch modal” button that opened it. This creates an ergonomic keyboard flow through the page.

Examining the Visibility Technique Radio Buttons

We can also see focus management in action with the radio buttons that select the different visibility techniques in the Component Sandbox.

When you have a set of radio buttons each with the same name, the group becomes become one tab stop. You can then use the Arrow keys to move through the individual radio buttons.

Think About Your User’s Experience

Whether you’re working with a modal or a radio group or a custom component like a date picker, you always need to think about the user’s experience.

What keyboard events will you support? Where will focus go? How should the screen reader experience work?

There are a lot of existing navigation patterns you can follow. Remember to test what you implement with the keyboard and screen readers as well as with people with disabilities!
